issue.body:
A bug was introduced in #1587.

The HTTP Host header already includes the port [http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec14.html#sec14.23], and there is no such thing as a Port header. Therefore Sails doesn't work behind properly-configured proxies: it only works behind misconfigured ones.

The solution is to use the actual HTTP Host header, which -- unfortunately -- Express truncates. A simple copy/paste from Express' `request.js` will give the host and port, straight from a valid HTTP request:

```javascript
  var trustProxy = req.app.get('trust proxy');
  var host = trustProxy && req.get('X-Forwarded-Host');
  host = host || req.get('Host');

  req.baseUrl = req.protocol + "://" + host;
```

With this change, the developer need only enable `trust proxy` to work behind any HTTP-compliant reverse proxy.

